  "prompt": "What is the legal history of money laundering prohibitions?",
  "response": "Here's an overview of the legal history of money laundering prohibitions:\n\n1. Early Origins:\n- Informal anti-money laundering (AML) practices date back to medieval banking systems\n- Emerged as a formal legal concept in the 1930s during prohibition era in the United States\n\n2. Initial Legislative Developments:\n- Bank Secrecy Act of 1970 (United States)\n- First comprehensive legal framework addressing financial transaction reporting\n- Required banks to report large cash transactions\n\n3. International Expansion:\n- 1989: Financial Action Task Force (FATF) established\n- Developed international standards for combating money laundering\n- Created global recommendations for national legal frameworks\n\n4. Major Legislative Milestones:\n- 1986: Money Laundering Control Act (US)\n- 1990: European Union's first AML directive\n- 2001: USA PATRIOT Act significantly expanded AML regulations\n- Criminalized money laundering as a specific federal offense\n- Imposed stricter reporting requirements\n\n5. Modern Regulatory Approach:\n- Comprehensive international cooperation\n- Enhanced technological tracking mechanisms\n- Expanded definitions of financial crimes\n- Increased penalties and enforcement mechanisms\n\nThis progression reflects growing global recognition of money laundering as a significant financial and criminal threat.",
